There seem to be scenarios where the value returned by getAppLastLoadedTimeInMs can go backwards in time during a reload, which I find really confusing.

I think if you want to solve the problem accurately then it needs to be modeled in the state with a new `coreLoadState: LoadState` property and handled in the reducer layer.

Would this work?

```
on(pluginListFetchRequested):
  pluginListLoadState = {...pluginListLoadState, state: LOADING}
  coreLoadState = {...coreLoadState, state: LOADING}
on(polymerRunsFetchRequested):
  polymerRunsLoadState = {...polymerRunsLoadState, state: LOADING}
  coreLoadState = {...coreLoadState, state: LOADING}
on(pluginListFetchSuccess):
  pluginListLoadState = {state: LOADED, lastLoadTime: Date.now()}
  if (pluginLoadState.state === LOADED && polymerRunsLoadState.state === LOADED):
    coreLoadState = {state: LOADED, lastLoadTime: pluginListLoad.lastLoadTime}
on(polymerRunsFetchSuccess):
  polymerRunsLoadState = {state: LOADED, lastLoadTime: Date.now()}
  if (pluginLoadState.state === LOADED && polymerRunsLoadState.state === LOADED):
    coreLoadState = {state: LOADED, lastLoadTime: polymerRunsLoadState.lastLoadTime}
// TODO: Handle failed states
```

Then getCoreDataLoadedState and getAppLastLoadedTimeInMs become trivial.

